I take music today as the target because the question of influence only tells us something new if it has some parameters, since it involves so many domains e.g. influence on a specific musical form, influence in specific countries or a specific school, influence on other artistic forms. Talking simply of influence is pretty vague, and I don't really need a list of citations to know that Beethoven is the most notable major composer, but the influences of contemporary composers might tell you something about what music is being made today. The list itself is not really worse or better than the list of major composers most people would discover if they just googled classical music, so I wouldn't say it's bad for beginners but the ideal situation in that case would be more curated recommendations from a person with a specific taste. The objectionable part of the list is not that its contents are bad but that it suggests that Beethoven is great because of academic citations. Ultimately, for a beginner, a tailored approach is always going to be more effective and give you more to hang your hat on than a simple list.
